# An class can extends another class and implements another interface at the same time
    Example:
            interface Calculator2 {}
            class Calculator1 {}
            class MyCalc extends Calculator1 implements Calculator2{}

# You can create an variable inside the interface and you have to do initialization of that variable is compulsory
    and By-Default variable inside the interface will be public, static, and final
    Example:
            interface Demo {
                int a = 30;
                public static final int b = 10; // variable 'a' will also look the same as variable 'b' By-Default
             }

# You can also able to implement Concrete Method inside the INTERFACE and for that you have use the keyword Default
    and it will be inherited to implementing class and you are allowed to override default method in the implementing class
    Example:
            interface Demo {
                default void display{                // default keywords are allowed only inside Interface
                    System.out.println("Hello");
                }
            }

# You can also able to implement Static Methods and Private Methods inside the INTERFACE and you cannot access the static method of interface from the
    class implementing the interface
    Example:
            interface Demo {
                static void display1 {
                    System.out.println("Hey");
                }
                private void display2 {
                    System.out.println("Welcome");
                }
            }

            and inside main method you can access the static method of interface using interface name
            like Demo.display1()

# Advanced Concepts of Interfaces

    1. Interfaces Cannot Be Instantiated, but Their References Can Be Created
    Explanation:
    Interfaces in Java define a contract (a set of methods) that implementing classes must follow,
    but they do not hold the state or implementation details themselves. This means you cannot create
    an instance of an interface. However, you can create a reference variable of an interface type,
    which can be used to refer to objects of any class that implements the interface. This feature
    is pivotal for achieving polymorphism, where the implementation details are hidden behind
    interface references, allowing for flexible code that can work with any new implementation of the interface.

    2. A Class Implements an Interface, but a Interface can extends other Interface
    Explanation:
    In Java, a class uses the keyword implements to adhere to the specifications of an interface.
    This means the class agrees to perform the specific actions the interface defines.
    On the other hand, an interface can extend another interface using the extends keyword,
    inheriting its method declarations. This allows for a hierarchy of interfaces,
    each building on or specializing the behavior defined by its parent.

            Example:

            interface Movable {
                void move();
            }

            interface Flyable extends Movable {
                void fly();
            }

            class Airplane implements Flyable {
                public void move() {
                    System.out.println("Airplane moves forward.");
                }

                public void fly() {
                    System.out.println("Airplane flies.");
                }
        }
            Here, Flyable extends Movable, adding a new capability. Airplane implements Flyable, and thus must define both move and fly.

            Q) Can interfaces extend other interfaces?
            Ans: Yes, they can extend multiple interfaces.
            Explanation: In Java, interfaces can extend one or more other interfaces. This allows a form of multiple inheritance
                         where interfaces inherit methods from multiple sources.

    3. An Interface Can Be Empty and Is Known as a Marker or Tagged Interface
    Explanation:
    An interface with no method declarations is known as a marker or tagged interface. These interfaces do not define
    any behaviors but serve to mark or identify a class as eligible for special processing. This can influence
    how objects of these classes are handled by other parts of your application or by Java itself.

        Example:

        interface Serializable {
        }

        class Employee implements Serializable {
            // Class details
        }
    Serializable is a marker interface that indicates objects of Employee can be serialized. It does not contain any methods
    but serves a critical role in identifying serializable classes.

    4. Interfaces Can Be Used to Achieve Multiple Inheritance in Java
    Explanation:
    Java does not support multiple inheritance through classes to avoid the "diamond problem,"
    where a class inherits from two classes that have conflicting implementations of the same method.
    However, Java allows a class to implement multiple interfaces, thereby enabling a form of multiple inheritance.
    Since interfaces only declare methods without defining them, this approach avoids ambiguity and conflict.

    Key Points:
    1. Interfaces cannot be instantiated, but their reference variables can point to objects of classes that implement the interface.
    2. A class implements an interface, and an interface can extend another interface.
    3. A marker interface has no methods and is used to mark classes for special processing.
    4. A class can implement multiple interfaces, enabling multiple inheritance.

    Conclusion:
    Interfaces are really helpful for making Java programs more flexible and easy to expand.
    They allow different classes to follow the same basic rules, but each class can choose how
    to do things its own way. This keeps the code organized and easy to change. Interfaces also
    make it possible for classes to get features from more than one source and allow them to work in different ways at the same time
